properties.webBody:
This Community Information message is being issued for Briagolong, Cobbannah, Culloden, Fernbank, Glenaladale, Lindenow South, Stockdale, The Fingerboards, Valencia Creek, Wuk Wuk and surrounding areas. 

  • The bushfire at Duffy Rd is not yet contained.
  • Recent rain has dampened fire activity, however there is still active fire within  the  burnt area as logs and trees continue to burn.
  • Firefighters continue to black out in steep, challenging terrain. The reinforcement of containment lines remains a priority.
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
  • There are still road closures due to active fire and hazardous trees.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures. For road closures on public land check the FFMVic website (www.ffm.vic.gov.au/permits-and-regulations/closures-of-parks-and-forests)
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 20/10/2023 02:50 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.  
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon:

MINOR FLOODING HAS EASED AT ROSEDALE

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Tuesday, rainfall totals up to 15 mm have been recorded across the Latrobe Rivercatchment.

No significant rainfall is forecast until this Sunday.Renewed river level rises are possible along the Latrobe River with forecast rainfall from Sunday, but are likely to remain below the minor flood level.

Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon:

No further flooding is expected along the Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon.

The Latrobe River at Rosedale (Main Stream) is currently at 3.91 metres and steady, below the minor flood level (4.00 m).

The Latrobe River at Rosedale (Main Stream) is expected to remain below the minor flood level.


The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area. 
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Torrumbarry to Barham.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT BARHAM WHERE MODERATE FLOODING IS POSSIBLE FROM LATER THIS WEEK.

Upstream flows from the Murray River combined with floodwaters from the Goulburn River catchment have caused minor flooding along the Murray River at Barham. 

The main flood peak along the Murray River is approaching Echuca where the river level is expected to remain below the minor flood level (93.5 metres

Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham:
Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Barham.  River levels at Echuca, Torrumbarry Weir, and Barham and are rising and likely to continue rising over the rest of the week into next week

The Murray River at Barham is currently at 5.60 metres and rising, with minor flooding. The Murray River at Barham may reach the moderate flood level (5.80 metres) from later this week.

This warning is for communities in Victoria. Floods have different impacts on either side of the Murray River. For information and warnings relevant to NSW, visit www.hazardwatch.gov.au. Always follow advice from your State’s emergency services
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 18/10/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Community Information message is being issued for Loch Sport, Paradise Beach. 

  • Firefighters continue to extinguish hot spots on the fire edge, to prevent any further spread of the fire.  
  •  Fire fighting aircraft will be regularly patrolling the area. 
  •  Please obey all traffic management signage and directions. Remember to slow down to 40 km per hour when passing emergency vehicles.  This is for your own safety and for the safety of our firefighters.
  •  Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
  •  Recent rainfall has assisted with fire suppression, however communities need to remain aware of fires near them and monitor for changes in conditions.  
  •  We expect to have this fire fully controlled within the coming days.
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 18/10/2023 11:30 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.  
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
